    cellular: { title: "Transfusion Physiology", content: "Blood product transfusion in the ICU requires understanding of indications, risks, and transfusion thresholds. Restrictive transfusion strategies (hemoglobin trigger 7 g/dL for most ICU patients) are equivalent or superior to liberal strategies (trigger 10 g/dL) in most critically ill populations. Packed red blood cells (PRBCs) increase oxygen-carrying capacity. Fresh frozen plasma (FFP) replaces all coagulation factors. Platelets provide hemostatic function. Cryoprecipitate concentrates fibrinogen, factor VIII, vWF, and factor XIII. Massive transfusion protocols (MTP) are activated for hemorrhagic shock requiring ≥10 units PRBCs in 24 hours or ≥4 units in 1 hour, using balanced ratios of 1:1:1 (PRBC:FFP:platelets). Transfusion reactions range from mild febrile/allergic to life-threatening anaphylaxis, TRALI, and hemolytic reactions." },
    riskFactors: ["Active hemorrhage requiring resuscitation", "Symptomatic anemia (tachycardia, dyspnea, chest pain) with Hgb <7", "Acute coronary syndrome with Hgb <8", "DIC with active bleeding requiring factor replacement", "Massive transfusion activating MTP", "Thrombocytopenia with bleeding or procedure planned", "Coagulopathy from liver failure or anticoagulation reversal", "Exchange transfusion for sickle cell crisis"],
